    "summary": "Repair contributor PR #90217 so the symlinked doctor state-integrity regression runs only when directory symlinks can actually be created, without module-import filesystem side effects.",
    "pr_title": "test: make doctor state integrity symlink test robust on Windows",
    "pr_body": "What Problem This Solves\n\nRepairs #90217 so the doctor state-integrity symlink regression can run on Windows when directory symlinks or junctions are available, while staying robust on environments where symlink creation is restricted.\n\nWhy This Change Was Made\n\nThe original contributor change correctly targets the Windows skip, but hydrated Copilot review found two blockers: the capability check only gated Windows, and the probe mutated the filesystem at module import time. This repair should move the capability check into the test lifecycle or test body and gate the regression on actual directory symlink capability for every platform.\n\nUser Impact\n\nTest-only change. It improves cross-platform regression coverage without changing runtime doctor behavior.\n\nEvidence\n\n- Source PR: https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw/pull/90217 by @aniruddhaadak80.\n- Current main still skips the symlink regression on win32.\n- Validation: pnpm test src/commands/doctor-state-integrity.test.ts; pnpm check:changed.",
